                                                                                                               SPORT BRIEFS
                                            Milan deny Abu Dhabi report  Milan: AC Milan has denied a report that the Abu Dhabi United group will purchase 40 per cent of the club. Milan and club president Silvio Berlusconi rsquo;s Fininvest holding company issued a joint statement saying that ldquo;the news has no basis rdquo;.  Italy rsquo;s leading newspaper, Corriere della Sera, reported Tuesday that after failing to purchase Kaka, Abu Dhabi United had switched its focus to buying part of Milan. The paper did not cite any sources, but said the offer would be euro500 million ($640 million).  Wada move  Lausanne: The head of the World Anti-Doping Agency rejected calls on Tuesday for athletes to be given a break from out-of-competition testing during holidays. Wada president John Fahey insisted there will be no changes to the whereabouts testing rule in the short term, saying any possible reform might be at least one year away. Fahey said Fifa and Uefa rsquo;s suggestion to give athletes a holiday break from testing would undermine anti-doping controls and give cheats time to start doping with impunity.  Big W return  Wimbledon: Former Wimbledon champions Andre Agassi and Steffi Graf will return to the All England Club in May to try out the playing conditions under the new Centre Court roof. Agassi and Graf mdash; who are now married mdash; will join Kim Clijsters and Tim Henman for a series of exhibition matches on May 17.  Table tennis  New Delhi: India rsquo;s Soumyajit Ghosh will figure among five young paddlers to be trained by Peter Karlsson as part of the International Table Tennis Federation rsquo;s lsquo;With the Future in Mind rsquo; project.  ICC meeting  Calcutta: The following are the details of the opening day ICC Chief Executives rsquo; Committee (CEC) meeting in Johannesburg:   Future Tours Programme (FTP) post-2012 mdash; The meeting discussed options for the international schedule when the current FTP concludes in May 2012. l Promoting Test cricket mdash; The members of the CEC discussed the measures put in place to promote Test cricket ahead of the upcoming series between South Africa and Australia. l ICC Anti-Doping Code (2009) mdash; The meeting heard that the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) has confirmed the ICC Anti-Doping Code (2009) is WADA-compliant. l Anti-Corruption and Security Unit (ACSU) mdash; The CEC was given a briefing by ACSU general manager and chief investigator Ravi Sawani.  Sensor check  Calcutta: In a bid to crack down on illegal bowling action, the International Cricket Council in association with the Marylebone Cricket Club will fund a scheme to develop a wearable, real-time electronic sensor to record and monitor bowling action during delivery. Bowlers with suspect actions will be invited to wear an electronic sensor during matches to determine whether they are throwing.   
